## What Is Philosophy?

Philosophy is the disciplined attempt to answer fundamental questions using reason, argument, and careful analysis. Unlike science, which relies on experiment and observation, philosophy addresses questions that cannot be settled by empirical data alone: What is the nature of reality? What can we really know? What makes an action right or wrong?

Philosophy was born in ancient Greece when thinkers like Thales of Miletus began seeking natural (rather than purely mythological) explanations for the world. His successors — Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle — refined the practice of philosophical argument into a systematic discipline that has never been surpassed in its influence.

## Branches of Philosophy

:::dropdown Metaphysics — The Study of Reality
Metaphysics asks: What is real? What exists? Does God exist? Do souls exist? What is the nature of time and space?

Traditional Platonic metaphysics held that ultimate reality is abstract and immaterial — the world of "Forms" or "Ideas." Latter-day Saint theology takes a radically different stance: God the Father has a glorified, tangible body of flesh and bones (D&C 130:22), and "all spirit is matter, but it is more fine or pure" (D&C 131:7). This is a materialism unlike any other philosophical tradition.
:::

:::dropdown Epistemology — How Do We Know?
Epistemology asks: What is knowledge? What can we be certain of? How do we distinguish knowledge from mere belief?

Western philosophy has wrestled with skepticism since Descartes asked whether a deceiving demon could make all our beliefs false. Latter-day Saint thought offers a distinctive answer: knowledge comes not only through reason and the senses but through the **Holy Ghost**, who can witness truth to the spirit directly — a broader conception of evidence that does not abandon reason but expands it.
:::

:::dropdown Ethics — How Should We Live?
Ethics asks: What is good? What do we owe each other? The three great Western ethical traditions each capture important truths:

- **Virtue Ethics** (Aristotle): The goal of life is *eudaimonia* (flourishing) achieved through developing virtuous character.
- **Deontology** (Kant): Morality consists of categorical duties — act only on principles you could will to be universal laws.
- **Utilitarianism** (Mill): The right action is whatever produces the greatest good for the greatest number.

Latter-day Saint ethics draws on divine command (God's revealed will) and virtue (developing a Christlike character), aiming not merely to follow rules but to become like God.
:::

:::dropdown Logic — The Science of Valid Reasoning
Logic is the study of what makes an argument valid. Aristotle developed the first systematic logic in his *Organon*, using syllogisms to represent valid inference. Modern symbolic logic (Frege, Russell) extended this into a mathematical calculus that underlies computer science and mathematics.

Key concepts: valid vs. sound arguments, deduction vs. induction, fallacies (ad hominem, straw man, false dilemma, etc.).
:::

:::dropdown Aesthetics — The Philosophy of Beauty
Aesthetics asks: What is beauty? What makes something a work of art? Why do we value art and beauty?

Plato worried that art could corrupt the soul by appealing to emotion over reason. Aristotle responded that art (especially tragedy) provides *catharsis* — a healthy purging of emotion. Kant argued that aesthetic judgment is universal in form even if not in content.
:::

## Major Philosophers

| Philosopher | Dates | Key Contribution |
|---|---|---|
| Thales | ~624–546 BC | First philosopher; sought natural explanations of the world |
| Socrates | ~470–399 BC | The Socratic method; virtue as the highest good |
| Plato | ~428–348 BC | Theory of Forms; the *Republic*; philosopher-kings |
| Aristotle | ~384–322 BC | Logic, virtue ethics, biology, metaphysics |
| Descartes | 1596–1650 | "I think, therefore I am"; mathematical rationalism |
| Kant | 1724–1804 | Categorical imperative; the limits of pure reason |
| Hume | 1711–1776 | Radical empiricism; skepticism about causation |
| John Stuart Mill | 1806–1873 | Utilitarianism; liberty and individual rights |

## Philosophy and Latter-day Saint Thought

Joseph Smith taught that "the glory of God is intelligence" (D&C 93:36) and that Latter-day Saints should seek learning "out of the best books" (D&C 88:118). Philosophical training:

- Sharpens the ability to identify logical fallacies
- Equips members to engage thoughtfully with critics and seekers
- Helps clarify the logical structure of doctrinal claims
- Provides tools for ethical reflection beyond simple rule-following

Philosophical study is not a threat to faith — it is one of the tools God has given us to understand the world He created.

